<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06332244 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06332244 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  COMPUTER; AID; STUDENT; COLLEGE; EDUCATION; FUTURE; EMPLOYMENT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Students at East Side Union High School District now have finger-tip access tohundreds of scholarships, job and career opportunities, university choices andeven military options.;   The Electronic Scholarship Search Program has beeninstalled this semester in the district's 10 high schools, after long-awaitedfunds from the Santa Clara County Office of Education.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Extra 4  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  COMPUTERS AID SEARCH FOR CAREER OPTIONS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Also ran in EAST1, EX3/2  </MEMO><TEXT>     &quot;I think if I had something like this in high school I could have made someother choices in the direction I took,&quot; said Marsha Dixon, career servicestechnician at Overfelt High School, who shows students how to tap into thecomputer program.;   In a few punches of the keys, students can findscholarships listed in a wide range of categories, including parents' club orunion affiliation, fields of study and ethnicity. Prospective youngjournalists, for instance, can punch in the career options section of theprogram and look forward to &quot;a great deal of control over their daily workschedule . . . long, irregular hours at times, and deadlines.&quot;;   Throughcounseling referrals and walk-ins, as many as 10 youths a day have asked aboutand used the program, Dixon said.;   &quot;This is becoming real popular,&quot; shesaid. &quot;We had one who came in first period, came back for lunch, then he hadto find out what union his dad belonged to, so he came back again. They reallylike working on the computer. It's amazing.&quot;;   The program, part of theCalifornia Career Information System, came about after decade-long efforts byformer district trustee Henry Gage to unlock interest on state funds held bythe Office of Education, district officials said. The East Side district,which received $1.5 million of the funds, received one of the larger shares ofthe interest. Gage asked that some of the money be used to set up theElectronic Scholarship program.;   School counselors are targeting high schoolseniors for use of the program, which is accessible from three to 11 terminalsat East Side schools, said district guidance coordinator Howard Trekell.;  &quot;It's been a long process taking several years to get to this place,&quot; he said.&quot;Most schools have this information, but usually it's in books.&quot;;   Besidesseniors, Dixon said the program should be available for students down throughthe junior high years.;   &quot;I'd love to bring every freshman in here and putthem through this,&quot; she said. &quot;Especially with the way they keep cuttingbudgets and cutting budgets. How soon will it be before we have no counselors?&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  E. MARK MORENO, Special to the Mercury News  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911127  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  418  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, November 27, 199100332244,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>